terioles followed by venules","Simultaneous vasodilation of arterioles and venules","Vasodilation of venules followed by arterioles","Vasoconstriction of venules followed by arterioles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vascular changes in acute inflammation follow a specific sequence. \u003Cstrong\u003EVasodilation of arterioles followed by venules\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct sequence, leading to increased blood flow to the affected area. This results in the cardinal signs of inflammation: heat and redness (due to increased blood flow) and swelling (due to increased vascular permeability).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasoconstriction of arterioles followed by venules\u003C/strong\u003E would decrease blood flow and impair the inflammatory response. A brief period of vasoconstriction may occur immediately after injury, but this is rapidly followed by vasodilation. \u003Cstrong\u003ESimultaneous vasodilation of arterioles and venules\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the process occurs in a sequential manner, beginning with arterioles. \u003Cstrong\u003EVasodilation of venules followed by arterioles\u003C/strong\u003E describes the incorrect sequence. Arterioles, which control blood flow into capillary beds, must dilate first to increase blood flow to the affected area. \u003Cstrong\u003EVasoconstriction of venules followed by arterioles\u003C/strong\u003E would impair the inflammatory response by reducing blood flow and preventing the migration of inflammatory cells to the site of injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis vascular response is mediated by various inflammatory mediators including histamine, prostaglandins, and nitric oxide. The increased blood flow and vascular permeability allows plasma proteins and inflammatory cells to migrate to the site of injury to begin the healing process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute inflammation causes vasodilation beginning in arterioles followed by venules, leading to increased blood flow.","Vasodilation in acute inflammation increases vascular permeability allowing plasma proteins and cells to migrate to injured tissue.","The cardinal signs of inflammation (heat, redness, swelling) are direct results of vasodilation and increased vascular permeability."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Punchard NA, Whelan CJ, Adcock I. The Journal of Inflammation. J Inflamm (Lond). 2004 Sep 27;1(1):1. doi: 10.1186/1476-9255-1-1. PMID: 15813979; PMCID: PMC1074343","Margraf A, Lowell CA, Zarbock A. Neutrophils in acute inflammation: current concepts and translational implications. Blood. 2022 Apr 7;139(14):2130-2144. doi: 10.1182/blood.2021012295. PMID: 34624098; PMCID: PMC9728535"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97412"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14950"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97412"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T16:23:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T16:23:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7638"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115409"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{